6. Carried out integration testing;
7. End User Testing and re-works 
8. Undertook Data Migration activity; 
9. Go-Live The Project followed the water fall approach. There was site preparation and application preparation carried out. The site preparation entailed:
1. Client visits to business process requirements of key budget 
process i.e. MTEF, BFP , MPS and Estimates; 
2. Validation of Server Configuration;
3. Examination of Servers and Back-up mechanism;
4. Installation and configuration of the SharePoint, SQL Server; 
5. Deployment of Performance Budgeting System and Supporting Go-Live.
6. Interface requirements with other key applications – IFMIS, IPPS & Aid Management.
Train the Trainer Approach
During implementation we used a modular wise training approach whereby the application was broken down into modules and each module assigned to a user per location. We also carried out practical training in a central location. We simulated a typical location set-up where a user would log-in with their credentials and they were taken through what they would do when they went back to their respective locations. We trained super-users who would later be the first line of support.
Project Management
A Hybrid Project Management team was setup and it comprised a Key Project Head who managed project leads for different components – application, hardware, and installations. A strong project management practice was put in place to ensure all activities were conducted on time and with quality. The project management team was further advised by a team of Public Financial Management (PFM) Advisors from Techno Brain who have experience of over 20 years in implementing Financial Management Systems and processes across the world; working with different donors and development partners. To monitor the progress of the implementation, a steering committee was also setup which included team of experts, Project Manager from MoFPED and other suppliers. Steering committee meetings were held every month.
The project was managed jointly by our Project Manager and the 
MoFPED Project Manager who were tasked with the following activities:1. Review SRS;
2. Conduct monthly reviews; 
3. Validate the process documents; 
4. Conduct project team meetings; 
5. Conduct security assessment after deployment and installation of System; 
6. Manage the end user training; 
7. Conduct Commissioning and hand over of PBS. 

Roles of GovernmentChallenges
Each of the members had distinct roles, the roles of 
MoFPED were:
1. Provide a government Project Manager and focal 
point of contact;
2. Convene the Project Launch meeting and invite the other stakeholders; 
3. Convene the Steering Committee meetings;
4. Convene the weekly project meetings; 
5. Facilitate the necessary MDA visits; 
6. Validate and approve the process documents;
7. Provide documentation on GOVT processes; 
8. Provide clarification during development of the Software specifications document; 
9. Participate in end user testing; 
10. Convene and supervise the Training; 
11. Provide and validate master data before data migration; 
12. Go-live support; 
13. Post go live support;
14. Convene administration training. During the project implementation we faced the following challenges:
1. Most of the processes were completely manual with 
very little computerization;
2. MoFPED’s understanding of the process for development using SharePoint controls was limited;
3. Some locations were very remote and didn’t have proper connectivity thus the system performance and availability were affected, hence we needed to create an offline functionality; 
4. MoFPED users and developers lacked capacity and knowledge on the PFM processes and needed re-orientation training before being trained on the application; 
5. Stake holder non-availability from various other ministry affected the Interface scope of deliverables;
6. Change management- getting users to accept and use the system was taxing;
7. Unreliable bandwidth for replication of data. 
Change Management
Change Management is a continuous process and we managed it in the following ways:
1. Project Launch- we invited select users from the 
various sites to brief them on what PBS was all about and what to expect during the project implementation; 
2. We trained the users and made them comfortable with the application; 
3. We conducted Change Management sessions during commissioning and hand over of equipment; 
4. Post go-live change management session were held in a central location.
Support
Techno Brain now provides  post-go live warranty and support structured in the following ways:
1. We have an Application and a Technical lead who 
continuously interacts with MoFPED for preventive maintenance services every month.
2. We provide 3 consultants stationed at Techno Brain’s office in Uganda to provide support and train MoFPED’s help desk team. 
3. We provide periodical visits and perform application security and performance checks when required. Our consultants visit MoFPED and interact with the users to understand and address their problems. 
4. We carry out retraining where necessary. 

Roll Out SkillsBenefits
Budget Process FlowThe Roll out was carried out by Consultants 
who are certified in the application and the following activities were carried out:
1. Data Migration;
2. Configuration of secured environment 
both at Central Data Centre and server rooms at each site;
3. Sound project management knowledge; 
4. Technical and Functional Consultants with knowledge on PFM processes; 
5. Understanding of PFM processes with business rules for government Budgeting process; 
6. Setting up the workflows and approval hierarchies; 
7. Setting up Budget rules, allocations and approvals. Since its successful implementation, the PBS brought with it a number of benefits to the Government budget management process. Among these were:
• Empowered actors in the budget processes to enhance quality 
of budget preparation; 
• Enabled greater linkage between budget outlays and performance of institutions;
• Enabled greater availability of the system at all the times to all budget units at central and local government levels;
• Mindful of the specific difference between processes for central and local government, it enhanced the notion of harmonized reporting for local governments; 
• Ensured better data integrity by having an inbuilt user log on security, coupled with responsibilities and work flow where needed;
• Created easier usability by improving navigation systems;
• Supported multi-period (financial year access) access and incorporated other end user features;
• Was easy to maintain using internal resources already at the MoFPED;
• The system  supported budget preparations activities for MALGS, coordination and consolidation activities for MoFPED; 
• The system also covered generation of in-year quarterly plans and performance budget reporting for MALGs and MoFPED during budget execution;
• The system produced more accurate records and improved financial reporting 
